Mr Kibet had paid Sh9,000 for the three- day stay. 

However, following the pin location they had been given, their ended abruptly on the Thika highway. They looked around and saw a compound on their left, the only one that appeared close to the pictures on the site. Thinking that was the house, they drove in to a rude shock when the occupant, an unamused old man, demanded to know the reason for their arrival. 






“We explained to him what had happened, and he was perplexed. He said he had never listed his house on any site, let alone Airbnb,” Mr Kibet says. “The old man, however, noted that it was not the first occurrence, as another traveller once knocked at his door having been ‘booked’ there.” 

Upon calling the contact person, a man named Elijah, he apologised to them and said there had been a double booking, but disconnected the call when asked to refund the amount paid via M-Pesa. 

Double bookings 

“I suspect that the houses do not exist, and if they do, it could be that the people running the account do double bookings and have money sent through M-Pesa. He chooses the person to stay at the home,” says Mr Kibet. 

He wrote a complaint to Airbnb and he is yet to get a response, a month later, nor a refund. 



