Mr Kibet’s is one of several reported cases where air is sold through Airbnb and other online reservation platforms like Booking.com. The popularity of this business model, which offers hospitality experience in between that of hotels and a rental houses at affordable rates, is attracting scammers who take advantage of existing loopholes to con unsuspecting customers. 

The con game happens in a number of ways, including listing of non-existent houses, using exquisite pictures to attract customers to pay more for sometimes dilapidated structures, and double bookings, where one party pays for an already occupied house. 

The catch here is that some clients are persuaded by the scammers to take the transactions offline after the sites link them up. 

While the sites work with rules, offering refunds to customers who change their minds not to occupy a property, sending money directly to the host takes away that insurance. 

Dubious characters lure clients to take this route, where they lose the digital protection and are likely to suffer. 

Reporting to the police is not an option many consider. Foi Wambui, a media personality and social media influencer, fell into such a trap in July, when she was looking for a place to spend her birthday weekend with family and friends. She went on Booking.com and came across Miotoni Mansion, which ticked all the boxes. 



