“It was a large, beautiful house with lots of rooms, a swimming pool and situated in Karen. I thought for a mansion it was also amazing that it fell within my price range. I just assumed it was because of the times we’re in,” says Wambui. 

It also happened to be available on the weekend she wanted. 

Pay full amount 

After booking, she got the host’s email address and a Kenyan number. She emailed the contact and also called the number but it wasn’t being answered. Some time passed before she received an email response and then an American number contacted her via WhatsApp. 

“She (the contact) went on to give me her email and Instagram handle. I checked them out and she had more than 10k followers on Instagram and some of the people I knew had even liked and commented on some posts. She then sent an invoice, asking me to pay the full amount two days before check-in. 

I told her what the rules said but she insisted that if the host hasn’t shared their bank details with the site, they can actually do this. It was strange, but everything looked good and professional,” recalls Wambui. 






Foi Wambui, a media personality and social media influencer, who fell victim to fraudsters on Booking.com.
Photo credit: Pool

 

She paid half the amount via M-Pesa to the host’s “brother”, who was staying in the house. The host informed her they would give her an extra night if she gave a review of the house thereafter. 



