These kinds of dubious dealings are said to be rampant not only in Kenya, but across the world, where clients have been warned to ensure due diligence in their bookings to avoid falling prey to fraudsters who have been targeting the popular website, Airbnb, that advertises thousands of holiday rentals, now in 191 countries. 

The site has proved safe as long as users stick to its terms and conditions and only send payments via its platform. 

Back in 2017, the Guardian reported how a British family lost more than £4,100 (Sh617,885) to sophisticated Airbnb fraudsters after booking what they thought was a holiday villa in Sicily, Italy, for three weeks. 

Like it happens in scam listings, the conmen managed to persuade holidaymakers to send payments via bank transfers instead of the official account. The listing and apartment turned out to be fake. 

And like many other victims, the family was left contemplating whether suing the site would be a worthy cause. 

Another method used by cyber thieves is creating fake sites that mirror the original Airbnb in every way, except minor details that would take a keen eye - a technology eye -  to notice. 

The bank accounts in such fake sites would obviously belong to the thieves. By the time the guest realises it, they’re stranded at an unknown place with luggage at hand with money gone. 



